# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1888-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The **1882 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 2, 1882.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural season for the American Association (AA) and seventh season for the National League (NL).
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Red Stockings won the AA pennant, while the Chicago White Stockings won the NL pennant.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association was established as a six-team league in cities not represented by the National League.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA was established with the expectation that it would have more of a "liberal policy" and better labor relations, threatening the puritanical NL, which itself had formal behavior codes with associated policies and procedures and a blacklist for players who did not comply to said rules.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The AA also refused to recognize the NL's reserve lists.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Three of the six teams of the American Association survive to this day as National League teams; the Cincinnati Red Stockings, Pittsburgh Alleghenys, and St.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings are today's Cincinnati Reds, Pittsburgh Pirates, and St.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season was the last for the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 schedule consisted of 80 games for all teams in the six-team American Association, and 84 games for all teams in the eight-team National League.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Each American Association team was scheduled to play 16 games against the other five teams, while each National League was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 80-game format was unique to the American Association's 1882 season.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League had been playing their 84-game schedule, since 1879, though 1882 would be their last.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see both leagues take on a 98-game format, playing 14 games each against their seven opponents.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams, while American Association Opening Day took place on May 2, featuring all six teams.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on October 2 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Providence Grays, while the American Association would see its final day of the regular season on October 1, featuring a game between the Louisville Eclipse and St.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (1 in AA, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season (though in the National League, standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and Pittsburgh Alleghenys had one tie game each.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Detroit Wolverines had three tie games.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Troy Trojans had two tie games each.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave Haymakers' Grounds (where they played for two seasons) and move to the Troy Ball Clubs Grounds, where they would play until they folded at the end of the season.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans continue to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing their first three home games of the season, May 16–18, as well as a fourth game on game 1 of a doubleheader May 30 at the park.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-major-league-baseball-season] The 1882 season saw three teams play their final games at respective ballparks, before moving to new ballparks for the 1883 season.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **St.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It played in the National Association league in 1875 and in the National League from 1876 to 1877.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] After a scandal over game-fixing, combined with financial problems, the St Louis Brown Stockings left the National League but continued to play as an independent team from 1878 to 1881.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Chris von der Ahe, a German immigrant, purchased the team prior to the 1882 season and joined the new American Association.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings posted a 37-43 game record in their first season in the American Association, giving them fifth place.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played at the Grand Avenue Grounds (which was later renamed Sportsman's Park) at the corner of Grand Avenue and Dodier Street in north St.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Before the 1882 season, Von der Ahe secured a place for the team in the American Association and provided funds to bring players to St.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Between 1882 and 1892, the team he built went on to win four American Association titles.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Al Spink, the team advisor, recommended Von der Ahe sign Charlie Comiskey.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Comiskey, who later played with the Chicago White Sox, was a skilled, young, first baseman who had been playing in Dubuque, Iowa.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Ned Cuthbert was a former professional player in St.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Although he had retired from baseball and worked as a bartender in St.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, Cuthbert remained prominent in the local baseball community.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He had encouraged Von der Ahe to purchase the team.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Von der Ahe hired Cuthbert to be his first captain, with all the duties of a field manager.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Cuthbert used his experience to attract several players to St.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Most of the first-year Browns originated in St.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis, including brothers Jack and Bill Gleason, pitcher Jumbo McGinnis, outfielder George Seward, and catcher Tom Sullivan.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In 1866, Gus Solari laid out a professional baseball field at Sportsman's Park, St Louis.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Sixteen years later, on May 2, 1882, the opening day of the St.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Louis Brown Stockings' 1882 season took place.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] Approximately 2,000 spectators watched the game for a fee of one quarter each.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team played numerous local teams in April exhibitions.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] McGinnis was the first pitcher and he started 45 of the team's 80 games.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] It was a lead off single in the first innings.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] He also scored the first run on Comiskey's three-base hit.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The team won their first game with a score of 9 runs to 7.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] In late May 1882, the team was in a tie for first place in its six-team league.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They were eight games over .500, putting them one game behind the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] There followed a seven-week period when the team lost sixteen more games than they won.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] They could not contend for the championship.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] During the season, more than 175,000 spectators attended the team's games.
[src:1888-world-series/1882-st-louis-brown-stockings-season] The favorite players on the team were Comiskey and McGinnis.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's second season in St.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri and its second season in the American Association.
[src:1888-world-series/1883-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 65–33 during the season and finished second in the American Association.
[src:1888-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1888-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1888-world-series/1884-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the team's third season in St.
[src:1888-world-series/1884-st-louis-browns-season] Louis, Missouri, and its third season in the American Association.
[src:1888-world-series/1884-st-louis-browns-season] The Browns went 67–40 during the season and finished fourth in the American Association.
[src:1888-world-series/1888-world-series] The **1888 World Series** was an end-of-the-year professional baseball season championship playoff series between the National League champion New York Giants and the old American Association champion St.
[src:1888-world-series/1888-world-series] Hall of Fame pitcher Tim Keefe went 4–0.
[src:1888-world-series/1888-world-series] This was the Browns' last appearance in a championship tournament and pre-modern-era World Series, the last of their four consecutive AA pennants.
[src:1888-world-series/1888-world-series] The club would later join the NL in 1892 and be renamed as the St.
[src:1888-world-series/1888-world-series] It would be 1926 before they would win their next league pennant.
